column4: <content>1 zw/w foto met opgekleefd formulier van The Art Institute of Chicago. Artist: Attrib. to Pieter Brueghel I; Title: The Blind; Medium: Pencil; Size: 218 x 317 mm; Collection: The Leonora Hall Gurley Memorial Collection. [Notitie in onbekend handschrift op foto]: 22. 1933; C 34977.</content>

<related_object.title>Art Institute of Chicago. Blind[?]. The paintings in Vienna (Baldass 1917, fig. 7 [= Ludwig Baldass, Unbekannte Bilder in Wien und Budapest, in: Jahrbuch des kunsthistorischen Instituts 11 (1917), pp. 1-15] and Basle N° 140, attributed by Baldass to Marten van Cleve (1527-8) differ in several respects from the drawing. The main difference apart from the missing dog & tree trunk and that that the spatial arrangement and background differ is in the first fallen blindman, who in the painting is seen with the legs turned to the spectator (developed from Napels), in the drawing he falls with his head (not visible) to the front and one leg the back. The drawing may be an original design by M. van Cleve (but it differs greatly from the drawing of cripples with fox-tails in Munich) or more likely a drawing by someone else after a lost composition by Bruegel, which inspired M. van Cleve.</related_object.title>
